@node "Distribution" "Distribution"
 Well, this package is @{b}FREEWARE@{ub}. And there is NO restriction concerning the
 distribution.

 You can (you should!) modify the @{b}csh-script@{ub}.
 You can disassemble/reassemble the progs (but you're advised to get the sources from me)
 You cannot blame me for any damage caused by this prog.@{b} @{fg shine}No warranty !@{ub}@{fg text}

 You should @{"contactĀme" link "Author" 0} if you use xList. Just to hear from you.

 The original archive contains the following files:
 xList   ------------>  should be in C: or in xList-GUI drawer
 xList-GUI
 xList-GUI.info
 xList_fra.guide
 xList_fra.guide.info
 xList_eng.guide
 xList_eng.guide.info
 xListing.sh  ------->  Should be in S: or CSH:
 FILE_ID.DIZ

@endnode

@node "xlistdoc" " xList v1.05"

 xList (reference to xDir for the crunching infos and List for the filenotes)
 is a small and simple directory listing utility, especially for module
 lists made using csh scripts (though csh is not required). It was at least
 awaited by two persons: @{"TheĀCyborg/NGC" link "greets" 0} and... me. So I give you the chance
 to be the 3rd :-)

 You must use xList-GUI to scan recursively dirs with xList.

     @{"Requirements" link "requir" 0}
     @{"Features" link "xlfeatures" 0}
     @{"Usage" link "xList_usage" 0}
     @{"Csh-script" link "script" 0}
     @{"Bugs" link "bugs" 0}
@endnode

@node "requir" "Requirements"

 - At least Kickstart 2.04 (OS v37) but only tested on v39...
 - The 'C:Sort' command (sorry, sorting is not built-in yet)
 - The ENV: and T: assigns

 So it should work on most computers (?).
 (I own a '030 A1200 + Fastmem, KS3.0)
@endnode

@node "xlfeatures" "Features"

 - Supports @{"some crunching formats" link Formats}...

 - Check for bad crunched files. Insert a "!" in the crunchtype (PP20->!PP2,
   xpk sublib->!XPK,...) in case of error. 

 - For the first time ever (?), a script-utility providing crunching-infos
   AND file comments (on the same line).

 - Doesn't show those ugly comments written by xScan (when you've got some
   files from an XFH partition).

 - Display DOS_comment of @{fg shine}directories@{fg text} (use it to write useful infos!).

 - Can write texts at the beginning and the end of the listing (see @{"Usage" link "xList_usage" 0}).

 - Able to display @{fg shine}Songname@{fg text} instead of Filename (under special conditions,
   see @{"Usage" link "xList_usage" 0} ).

 - Hides the .* files (like @{i}.EPDir@{ui}).

 - To speed up sorting: makes Sort resident, if not already.

 - @{b}Many arguments@{ub}, try them .... See @{"Usage" link "xList_usage" 0}.

 - Exit on Ctrl-C. 

 - Pure bit set (both reentrant and reexecutable). Can be made resident.
   Not safely reentrant if sorting is switched on (writes temp files in T:).
   But should not cause problems, as long as you don't want to trash your HD
   by scanning 2 dirs at the same time, do you ? :-)

 - Writes the number of files of the last scanned dir in ENV:xltotal and the
   total number of files since the 1st scanned dir in ENV:xlsumtot (get these
   env. variables via @{fg shine}$xltotal@{fg text} and @{fg shine}$xlsumtot@{fg text} in your scripts).

 - Bonus: a @{"CshĀscript" link "script" 0}.

 - It's my first proggy! (-a very nice feature,yeah-).

Note:
 xList is not related to XL (formerly called XList) by MindShadow/Foundation (J.Samuelson)
Give it a try (in util/cli) because it's a powerful fileidentifier (several hundreds of types known)
@endnode

@node Formats

 xList read the first 32 bytes of a file to get its type and decrunched size.

 - Supports @{"XPK" link "thanks" 0}, and some others crunchers: @{b}Powerpacker@{ub} (PP20),
   @{b}CrunchMania@{ub}, @{b}StoneCracker@{ub}Ā(S403/S404).

 - Supports @{b}LHA@{ub}:
   Contact me if you run a BBS and use xList for the Index !

   If you find an archive whose unpacked size is wrongly calculated, thanks
   to send it to me.
   Currently xList detects the archives generated by Lha Amiga and HP-UX.
   Are there other Lha formats out there ?
@endnode

@node "xList_usage" "xList usage"

 The options are in the order I implemented them, not in the most logical one.

 Let's see the AmigaDOS template:

  xList DIR/M,
        IT=INTROTEXT/K,
        NT=NOTOTALS/S,
        TR=TESTRIPP/S,
        TD=TESTDURATION/S,
        ET=ENDTEXT/K,
        NOSORT/S,
        NH=NOHEADER/S,
        FO=FILESONLY/S,
        FP=FULLPATH/S,
        H2=HEADER2/S,
        LF/N/K,
        DL=DRAWLIMITS/S,
        COF=COUNTONLYFILES/S,
        SN=SONGNAME/S,
        SU=SHOWUSIZE/S,
        LA=LINEASPECT/N/K
        NC=NOCRUNCHINFOS/S
        SF=SHORTFILENAMES/S

 (AmigaDOS: M=Multi,K=Key,S=Switch,N=Numeric)

Note:
 if you specify several formatting args like SU and NC at the same time, there
 will be a meaningless output.


 @{b}DIR@{ub}
  Directories to scan. Current dir if not specified. Wildcards are NOT
  parsed by xList, currently only some Shells makes wildcards possible.

 @{b}IT=INTROTEXT@{ub}
  Followed by a filename, writes it before scanning.

 @{b}NT=NOTOTALS@{ub}
  Totals are not written if specified.

 @{b}TR=TESTRIPP@{ub}
  If specified, displays only modules with "Ripp" in the comments (hi Gry!)
  So you can write infos about the modules instead of "Ripped by ..."

 @{b}TD=TESTDURATION@{ub}
  If specified, displays only modules WITHOUT the duration ( [xx:xx] ) in
  the comment. A "[" must be its 1st or the 3rd ("- [") char.

 @{b}ET=ENDTEXT@{ub}
  Same as IT, but writes the given text at the end

 @{b}NOSORT@{ub}
  If specified, the listing of each dir WON'T be sorted by name.
  Sorting slows the output. So it'll be faster. And xList is again
  fully reentrant (but who wants to lauch 2 xList at the same time?).

 @{b}NH=NOHEADER@{ub}
  If specified, the dirname and its possible comment are not displayed.

 @{b}FO=FILESONLY@{ub}
  Hides dirs.

 @{b}FP=FULLPATH@{ub}
  Writes in the header the full path of this dir. (in fact, it won't
  cut the path part of the argument you gave to xList. So it is not really
  the full path _yet)

 @{b}H2=HEADER2@{ub}
  Another header. Affects only the header.
  Displays dir name and dir comments. The default header was suggested
  by Gryzor, while the other one was inspirated by Gryzor's lists.

 @{b}LF@{ub}
  LF=n put n LineFeeds after output. Useful in scripts.

 @{b}DL=DRAWLIMITS@{ub}
  Draw a line before the header, and another one right after it.

 @{b}COF=COUNTONLYFILES@{ub}
 If specified, dirs won't be counted in totals.

 @{b}SN=SONGNAME@{ub}
  Replaces Filename by Songname (only available on XPK packed mods, whose
  format supports Songname, which will be truncated to 16 characters,
  because these 16 chars are already in the XPK header, no need of
  depacking. There are 20 chars maxi in a PTK songname.)
  If the songname is too short (4 chars) or contains non-ascii values (>$7F)
  the filename will be typed.

 @{b}SU (SHOWUSIZE)@{ub}
  Prints unpacked size. Else (default) you can get it via ratio and crunched
  size, and there's more room for filename and comment.

 @{b}LA (LINEASPECT)@{ub} (Key)
  To specify the delimiter's aspect with DL.

 @{b}NC (NOCRUNCHINFOS)@{ub} (Switch)
  Doesn't write decrunched size, ratio, and filetype.

 @{b}SF (SHORTFILENAMES)@{ub} (Switch)
  Like the NC option, but there is less space for filenames. (18 chars)
@endnode

@node "script" "Csh-script"
 - About the script: not much to say... If you don't use Csh yet, try it. 
 Type "xListing" at the prompt (with 0 -pops up a dir requester- or 1 dir as
 argument) and a nice listing will be written in RAM:
 The directory will be recursively scanned (thanks to csh!)

 Please experiment yourself with it !
@endnode

@node "bugs" "Known bugs"

 When sorting is activated (default), you can't safely lauch several xLists
 at the same time. No more reentrant! (because of temporary files in T: used
 for the sorting)

 As you might have guessed, even if it's coded mainly in ASM, I used the Shell
 with the Sort command. It's lame, but sorting is so useful...

 By the way, if someone could help me with a 100% ASM sorting...And the
 recursivity into dirs...and the wildcard parsing... Until then, use either
 the csh script or xList-GUI.
@endnode

